---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead';
import Footer from '../components/Footer';
import Header from '../components/Header';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';

const canonicalUrl = new URL(Astro.url.pathname, Astro.site).toString();
const pageUrl = Astro.url.toString();
const rssUrl = new URL('rss.xml', Astro.site).toString();
const sitemapUrl = new URL('sitemap-index.xml', Astro.site).toString();
const generator = Astro.generator;
const currentPath = Astro.url.pathname;
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title={`About ¬∑ ${SITE_TITLE}`}
			description="Giorgio - what I'm working on and what I care about."
			canonicalUrl={canonicalUrl}
			pageUrl={pageUrl}
			rssUrl={rssUrl}
			sitemapUrl={sitemapUrl}
			generator={generator}
		/>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header currentPath={currentPath} />
		<main class="mx-auto w-full max-w-content px-4 py-16">
			<article class="space-y-10 font-mono text-[1.02rem] leading-[1.9] text-fog">
				<header class="space-y-2">
					<h1 class="text-[3rem] font-semibold text-ink">About</h1>
				</header>
				<p>
					Hi üëã! My name's Giorgio, but most people call me Gio. I studied Economics at Wilfrid Laurier
					University, taught myself how to write software, and co-founded a company while I was still
					in school. In 2016 I joined the <a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://www.nextcanada.com/next-36/">Next 36</a> program, which kicked off a deep focus on building
					systems and teams.
				</p>
				<p>
					The startup didn't make it, but the experience cemented that software is where I want to
					spend my time. From 2016 to 2020 I worked as a full stack engineer at <a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://setter.com/">Setter</a>, helping to scale a
					service company into a product-led organization.
				</p>
				<p>
					Along the way I built <a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://github.com/parlez-vous/">ParlezVous</a>, a side project written in Elm that rekindled my love for
					functional programming and small, focused tools. Elm remains one of my favorite languages
					for thinking clearly about state.</p>
				<p>
					Today I'm the technical lead and founding engineer at <a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://www.caribouwealth.com/">Caribou</a>, where I work on the
					systems that help people understand and act on their financial futures.
				</p>
				<section class="space-y-4">
					<h2 class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-mist/70">Links I find myself sharing</h2>
					<ul class="grid gap-2 text-sm text-mist">
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://www.reddit.com/r/technology/comments/85eri3/edward_snowden_facebook_is_a_surveillance_company/">Facebook is a surveillance company</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://edge.org/response-detail/11783">Kayfabe</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://www.thrivenotes.com/the-last-answer/">The Last Answer</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://galactanet.com/oneoff/theegg_mod.html">The Egg</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://paulgraham.com/love.html">Love ‚Äî Paul Graham</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://www.paulgraham.com/avg.html">Beating the Averages</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://www.thoughtcrime.org/blog/career-advice/">Career Advice</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://sivers.org/kimo">There's No Speed Limit</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://www.jasq.org/just-another-scala-quant/inverting-binary-trees-considered-harmful">On new age tech interview trends</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/13/john-steinbeck-letters-to-elizabeth-dream/?mc_cid=23a7c01a76&mc_eid=ec41677af4">The Death of Creative Culture</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://herpolhode.com/rob/utah2000.pdf">OS Research is Irrelevant</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://playbook.samaltman.com/">Startup Playbook</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://www.skyhunter.com/marcs/GentleSeduction.html">The Gentle Seduction</a></li>
						<li><a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://norvig.com/21-days.html">Teach Yourself Programming in Ten Years</a></li>
					</ul>
				</section>
				<blockquote class="border-l-2 border-accent/70 pl-4 text-sm text-mist">
					Just as there are odors that dogs can smell and we cannot, as well as sounds that dogs can
					hear and we cannot, so too there are wavelengths of light we cannot see and flavors we cannot
					taste. Why then, given our brains wired the way they are, does the remark, ‚ÄúPerhaps there are
					thoughts we cannot think,‚Äù surprise you? ‚Äî
					<a class="text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-dark" href="http://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1004020">Richard Hamming</a>
				</blockquote>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
